## Summary

I've created a short briefing on the agent-native application paradigm based on 
the documentation in your folder. The briefing has been written to the file:

**`output/campaign/research_assistant/run-004/notes/agent-native-paradigm-briefi
ng.md`** (397 words)

The briefing synthesizes the core concepts into a coherent narrative:

- **Problem**: Autonomous agents cannot be trusted to self-enforce safety 
constraints through prompts alone.
- **Solution**: An agent mesh—dedicated infrastructure that mediates all agent 
interactions and enforces policy independently of the agent's reasoning.
- **Key mechanisms**: Permission envelopes, HITL checkpoints, boundary policies,
resource budgets, and comprehensive audit trails.
- **Design philosophy**: Declarative specifications define envelopes of 
permitted runtime behavior (not static blueprints), pluggable agent kinds all 
route through the same enforcement chokepoint, and six formal safety invariants 
guarantee baseline trustworthiness regardless of what the LLM attempts.

The briefing positions this paradigm as the agent-native analogue to service 
mesh architectures in microservices—infrastructure-owned enforcement of 
safety-critical constraints at the mesh boundary rather than relying on 
application code to comply.
